title: Tidy Tuesday: Employed Status
description: Exploring Employed Status using a Tidy Tuesday dataset
contents:
Contents
Introduction
Exploration
Conclusion

Introduction
This is my first time participating in Tidy Tuesday. What is Tidy Tuesday? As explained in this website:

Tidy Tuesday is a weekly social data project in R where users explore a new dataset each week and share their findings on Twitter with #TidyTuesday. … rocks to learn from the friendly and talented Tidy Tuesday community and inspire your next great data visualization!

Yes, data visualization! However, I will focus more on developing Shiny app instead. To start off my first ever Tidy Tuesday, I will explore Employed Status
Exploration
The link of the full script can be found on my github page. So here is the summary of the shiny app:
Two sections:
Employment year: We look at the total employment by year (2015-2020) by industry. For this section, we can filter it by year. This graph is created using ggplot and then ggplotly() is used to make it an interactive plotly graph!

Employment breakdown: This is where we go deeper, and look at either gender, race or by total.


Conclusion
This is a very simple shiny app. I will try to participate in Tidy Tuesday every single week now, because it helps me to improve my data wrangling and shiny skills. Thanks for reading!

title: Working with date-time data: Lubridate & Janitor
description: Handling date-time data using Lubridate package & Janitor package in R-Studio
contents:
Contents
Introduction
Data Loading
Description
Exploring Data


Introduction
Dealing with date-time is something that I will usually avoid when using R. One of the reasons:
It can be frustrating: Due to the fact that there could be multiple types of date-time, or different languages (locale)
However, I had to deal with a few date-time datasets recently. By googling & researching, I found lubridate & janitor packages to be quite interesting to use. Two resources that I have been using & like:
R for Data Science
Lubridate package
Janitor package
Data Loading


# Libraries required

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)
library(readxl)
library(lubridate)


date_time <- read_excel(here("_posts/work-date-time/date-time.xlsx"))



Description
The dataset used in this blog contains 2 columns & 16,254 records :


glimpse(date_time)


Rows: 16,254
Columns: 2
$ Date      <chr> "44312", "44312", "44312", "44312", "44312", "4431~
$ Timestamp <dttm> 1899-12-31 17:39:29, 1899-12-31 14:13:53, 1899-12~

Date: Date of transaction made
Timestamp: Time of transaction made
Exploring Data
Looking at the structure of the dataset above, there are 2 problems.
Date column is not displaying properly
Timestamp column is not displaying properly. For example, 17:39:29 is displayed as 1899-12-31 17:39:29 when uploaded in R. Therefore we will need to extract just the timestamp later on
First problem: Date column
Lets have a look at the first problem:
Weird numeric format (44287, 44310, 44311, 44312). This happens because the date is in excel date format (it counts days). A similar problem can found in stack overflow
Multiple date formats in a column (04.01.2021, 1-Mei-2021, 27/5/2021)


date_time %>%
  count(Date, sort = TRUE)


# A tibble: 7 x 2
  Date           n
  <chr>      <int>
1 44312       7955
2 44310       6887
3 44311       1408
4 04.01.2021     1
5 1-Mei-2021     1
6 27/5/2021      1
7 44287          1

Fixing the numeric format to date is easy to solve using excel_numeric_to_date using the janitor package:


date_time_processed <- date_time %>%
  mutate(`Date 2` = excel_numeric_to_date(as.numeric(Date)))



So we managed to convert from numeric to date format (Compare Date column vs Date 2 column):


date_time_processed %>%
  count(Date, `Date 2`, sort = TRUE )


# A tibble: 7 x 3
  Date       `Date 2`       n
  <chr>      <date>     <int>
1 44312      2021-04-26  7955
2 44310      2021-04-24  6887
3 44311      2021-04-25  1408
4 04.01.2021 NA             1
5 1-Mei-2021 NA             1
6 27/5/2021  NA             1
7 44287      2021-04-01     1

Now we need to standardize the different date formats (04.01.2021, 1-Mei-2021 and 27/5/2021). To fix that, I will be using parse_date_time2 from lubridate package. Once the date is extracted, I will then convert it to date format. The process:
Using if_else() to find the missing values in “Date 2” column. For this case, the ones that failed to convert from numeric to date (04.01.2021, 1-Mei-2021 and 27/5/2021)
Parse 04.01.2021, 1-Mei-2021 and 27/5/2021 using parse_date_time2 and specify the pattern (%d%m%y) which is day, month and year.
Convert them to date format using as_date


date_time_processed <- date_time_processed %>%
  mutate(`Date 3` = if_else(is.na(`Date 2`),
                            parse_date_time2(Date, "%d%m%Y") %>% as_date(),
                            `Date 2`)) 



Checking it back, we managed to convert all them successfully (Date 3):


date_time_processed %>%
  count(Date, `Date 2` , `Date 3`)


# A tibble: 7 x 4
  Date       `Date 2`   `Date 3`       n
  <chr>      <date>     <date>     <int>
1 04.01.2021 NA         2021-01-04     1
2 1-Mei-2021 NA         2021-05-01     1
3 27/5/2021  NA         2021-05-27     1
4 44287      2021-04-01 2021-04-01     1
5 44310      2021-04-24 2021-04-24  6887
6 44311      2021-04-25 2021-04-25  1408
7 44312      2021-04-26 2021-04-26  7955

Second problem: Timestamp column
Now for the last problem, timestamp! This is pretty straightforward. Here is the process:
Extract the timestamp using format() using pattern “%H:%M:%S” which is hour, minute and second
I will then combine the Date 3 column with extracted Timestamp2 column to create a date-time column


date_time_processed <- date_time_processed %>%
  mutate(Timestamp2 = format(Timestamp, "%H:%M:%S"),
         Final_date = as_datetime(paste(`Date 3`, Timestamp2)))



The first 6 rows of our final_date column:


date_time_processed %>%
  select(Final_date) %>%
  head()


# A tibble: 6 x 1
  Final_date         
  <dttm>             
1 2021-04-26 17:39:29
2 2021-04-26 14:13:53
3 2021-04-26 20:43:55
4 2021-04-26 14:16:22
5 2021-04-26 11:53:45
6 2021-04-26 13:11:57

Thanks for reading!

title: Stemming: Malay Text
contents:
Contents
Introduction
Purpose of this blog post

Methods
First article
Second article

Conclusion

Introduction
Word stemming is a process that has been used widely in text mining by removing affixes in words to generate their respective root words. For example, “diambil” is reduced to its root word: “ambil.”
Purpose of this blog post
Word stemming is often used to reduce the size (eg: “diambil” is now treated as “ambil”) & to help increase the effectiveness and the accuracy of a research as explained by (Sembok and Bakar 2011). Hence, the purpose of this post is to compare two researches of word stemming (Malay text).
Methods
First article
The first is article from (Khan et al. 2017). The authors listed 4 Malay affixes:
Prefix : Beginning of a word
Suffix: End of a word
Infix: Middle of a word
Confix: Beginning and the end of the word.
Due to the complexity of the Malay language, they developed a dictionary of 9512 root-words to help handling uncertainty during the stemming process
Steps
Check dictionary: Check inputs for root words using the dictionary
Stop if all now root words
Or continue

Stem extrasuffix: (Khan et al. 2017) explained the extra suffix as "-nya"
Check dictionary: Check inputs for root words using the dictionary
Stop if all now root words
Or continue

Stem plural: If the word is plural, then stem to root word
Stem infix: If the word contains infix, then remove infix
Check dictionary again: Check inputs for root words using the dictionary
Stop if all now root words
Or continue

Stem prefix: If the word contains prefix, then remove prefix. Eg: “ter” & “per”
Special case: Prefix “mem” would be replaced with either “f” or “m”
The authors also checked if the word is less than 5 alphabets before stemming in order to prevent overstemming from happening

Check dictionary again: Check inputs for root words using the dictionary
Stop if all now root words
Or continue

Stem suffix: If the word contains suffix, then remove suffix. Eg: “nya” & “kan”
Again, if the word is less than 5 alphabets, they would not remove the suffix

Check dictionary again: Check inputs for root words using the dictionary
Limitations
Shorter prefix or suffix will always get ignored.
For example, "pem" will always be removed instead of “pe” . “Pemain”: “pem” will be removed instead of “pe” which results the word to be “ain” which completely changes the meaning of the word.

Second article
Similar to the first article, (Kassim et al. 2016) listed 4 Malay affixes:
Prefix : Beginning of a word
Suffix: End of a word
Infix: Middle of a word
Confix: Beginning and the end of the word.
Steps
The authors also used a dictionary to handle the uncertainty faced during the stemming process.
Check dictionary: Check inputs for root words using the dictionary
Stop if all now root words
Or continue

Stem infix: If the word contains infix:
Check dictionary
Remove infix

Stem confix: If the word contains confix:
Check dictionary
Remove confix

Stem prefix: If the word contains prefix:
Check dictionary
Remove prefix

Stem suffix: If the word contains suffix:
Check dictionary
Remove suffix

Limitations
Stemming names, places or brand names. For example
Ali (name)
Jerman (place)
Malaysiakini (brand-name)

Conclusion
This blog post compares two Malay word stemmers. Both (Khan et al. 2017) and (Kassim et al. 2016) used a dictionary in their respective stemmer. (Khan et al. 2017) proposed to find the pattern of "-nya" first, while (Kassim et al. 2016) proposed to find the pattern of infixation first.
Thanks for reading!



Kassim, Mohamad Nizam, Mohd Aizaini Maarof, Anazida Zainal, and Amirudin Abdul Wahab. 2016. “Enhanced Affixation Word Stemmer with Stemming Error Reducer to Solve Affxation Stemming Errors.” Journal of Telecommunication, Electronic and Computer Engineering (JTEC) 8 (3): 37–41.


Khan, Rehman Ullah, Fitri Suraya Mohamad, Muh Inam UlHaq, Shahren Ahmad Zadi Adruce, Philip Nuli Anding, Sajjad Nawaz Khan, and Abdulrazak Yahya Saleh Al-Hababi. 2017. “Malay Language Stemmer.”


Sembok, Tengku Mohd T, and Zainab Abu Bakar. 2011. “Effectiveness of Stemming and n-Grams String Similarity Matching on Malay Documents.” International Journal of Applied Mathematics and Informatics 5 (3): 208–15.

The graph is skewed to the right, which means there are more lower price houses as compared to the higher price houses.

  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format()) +

  scale_x_log10(labels = scales::comma_format()) +
  labs(title = "House Price (Histogram)",
       subtitle = "Log 10",
       x = "House Price",
       y = "Total")




Price vs Area (Sq Ft)
Notice that the most expensive house is only slightly higher than 5,000 sq ft in area size. We could also see that most of the houses are at the lower side of the price and the area size.


london %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = price, y = area_in_sq_ft, colour = house_type)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format()) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format()) +
  labs(title = "Price vs Area (Sq Ft)",
       x = "House Price",
       y = "Area (Sq ft)",
       colour = "House Type")




Area Size and Number of bathrooms
It appears that the total number of bathrooms and the total number of bedrooms are the same. If it does, that does not make sense at all.


london %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = no_of_bedrooms, y = no_of_bathrooms, colour = house_type)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format()) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format()) +
  labs(title = "Bedrooms and Bathrooms",
       x = "No of Bedrooms",
       y = "No of bathrooms",
       colour = "House Type")




Let’s check, just to be sure. We will check for the total number of receptions too


london %>%
  mutate(check_room = if_else(no_of_bedrooms == no_of_bathrooms,
                              "SAME",
                              "DIFFERENT"),
         check_reception = if_else(no_of_bedrooms == no_of_receptions,
                              "SAME",

We will use the logarithm of the house price for prediction. Features that we will use:
House Type
Area

City country

london <- london %>%
  mutate(price_log = log10(price))

london_predict <- london %>%

Tune Hyper-parameters
Split the data set into training and testing sets
We will then try to tune:
mtry
trees



library(tidymodels)

set.seed(1000)


london_split <- initial_split(london_predict)
london_train <- training(london_split)

We will be adding one extra process, where we will change city_contry into dummy variables


price_recipe <- london_train %>%

  step_dummy(city_county)



Workflow
Define a workflow


price_workflow <- workflow() %>%

We will then define model specifications


random_forest_model <- rand_forest(

Introduction
Last week, we had a request from a client. We were given a list of 600 stores and I needed to match those stores with the stores that we have in our database.
So, I used “fuzzyjoin” package in R to find the similarity between these stores based on the address list given.
For this project, I am not going to use the dataset given by the client (confidential). Instead, I am going to use a dataset available in Kaggle.
Dataset
It is a list of Target stores (as of April 2017). It has a lot of useful attributes such as operating hour, open date, and latitude & longitude. However, I will only be requiring the address column for this project:



library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(readr)
library(fuzzyjoin)
library(here)
 
targets <- read_csv(here("_posts/fuzzy-matching/1. Input Files/targets.csv")) %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  select(id, address_formatted_address)



I will copy this data set, but this time I will remove the vowels, and the id column


targets_missing <- targets %>%
  select(-id) %>%
  mutate(address_formatted_address = str_remove_all(
    tolower(address_formatted_address), 
    "[aeiou]"))



Next, I will use stringdist_left_join() to find the stores between the targets data frame and “targets_missing” data frame. I will then use slice_min to get the minimum value (distance score) for each of the store because I just want only a match per store, and I want it to be the closest distance. (Hence, the minimum value per store).


stores_matching <- targets %>%
  stringdist_left_join(targets_missing, by = "address_formatted_address",
                       method = "cosine", distance_col = "score")
 
stores_matching <- stores_matching %>%
  group_by(address_formatted_address.x) %>%
  slice_min(order_by = score)
